## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Forced stop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |

### Why This Must Change

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The entire approach must shift from **preemptive** (runtime injects exception) to **cooperative** (code checks for cancellation voluntarily).

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation was requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop.
                // The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No auto-rethrow — you control the loop, so just let it continue or exit |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | `Join` actually waits for the thread to finish; `Sleep` was just hoping |
| — | `_cts.Dispose()` | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers/callbacks |

---

### Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Cooperate

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), cancellation **won't take effect** until it returns — the token is only checked at loop boundaries. You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — cancellation stalls here
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
}

// ✅ GOOD — wakes up on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If using `Thread.Sleep` anywhere in the work:
```csharp
// ❌ Thread.Sleep ignores the token
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// ✅ Wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

### Common Mistakes to Avoid

1. **Not passing the token down the call chain** — If `ProcessItem` calls 5 methods deep and none accept the token, cancellation stalls until all that work finishes.

2. **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** — Only catch at the top-level loop. Let it propagate through inner methods.

3. **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — Leaks timer handles. Always `Dispose()` in `Stop()` or use `using`.

4. **Expecting cancellation to be instant** — It's cooperative. If `ProcessItem` does 30 seconds of CPU work with no checkpoint, cancellation waits 30 seconds. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive steps.
